{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PLAN-REVIEW REMEDIATION + claim (2026-06-30). Prior run BLOCKed on the missing OVERLAY_IDS enum vocabulary (E2/critical). Remediated: added the 11-value OVERLAY_IDS starter set (security/performance/i18n/a11y/db-migrations/docs/supply-chain/api-compat/iac/tests/llm-prompts) owned by WS1; pinned the single-structured-output wiring (one code_review_base_output schema with findings+recommend_overlays top-level keys; mode=structured NOT mode='findings' which strips non-findings); pinned the context-string shape; resolved the reuse-vs-import contradiction (assemble.py re-implements the diff-read, no import from code_review.py); pinned the coverage-gap note shape. Re-run -> VERDICT PASS, 0 blocking, signed.\n\nResidual 8 advisories triaged (all non-blocking nitpicks; gate is a structural floor):\n- A1 (T8, substantive, baked into implementation): 'drop out-of-enum overlay_id (not error)' must NOT be a strict JSON-Schema enum on overlay_id (mode=structured runs validate_structured -> would ERROR). Resolution: schema's overlay_id is a plain string; a deterministic registry helper filters recommend_overlays against OVERLAY_IDS, dropping unknowns. AC3 drop-test exercises that helper.\n- A3 (drift): the schema's overlay_id stays a plain string but the AGENT prompt enumerates OVERLAY_IDS; the no-drift guarantee is that the filter + prompt both derive from the one OVERLAY_IDS constant (a test asserts the constant is the single source).\n- A2/A5/A6/A8/A7 (ADR mention, 'Round-B' jargon, DiffContext-interface AC, AC ordering, P6): wording/sequencing nitpicks; the design is captured in the body. Left intentionally (over-fitting the finder bloats the ticket without improving implementability)."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782815671800396001,"uuid":"9aa14ef7-049c-4395-bd62-35241a32367a"}